    "For values of n that are very small, it is possible to compute r n (M 1) from the distribution of the nondecreasing score sequences.",
    "However, even for small n, this becomes computationally impossible due to the fact that the size of the sample space is 2 (n 2).",
    "Indeed, Epstein (1967) employed the distribution of the nondecreasing score vector up to n = 8, as provided by David (1959), to calculate the values of r 1 (M 1),.",
    ", r 8 (M 1).",
    "It is interesting to note that MacMahon (1923a) generated the score sequences and their frequencies up to n = 9."
  ],
